{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"04ee7946-7880-479d-b299-ddcf4560b3c3","content":"The template is **close but not ready** to publish. Here are the issues:\n\n### Missing (important)\n- **`$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation and editor support.\n- **`description`** — Missing entirely. This is what users see in `dotnet new search` results on NuGet. Without it, the template is effectively invisible.\n\n### Missing (recommended)\n- **`groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet so related templates (e.g., multi-language) can be grouped. Typically something like `\"MyCompany.WebApi\"`.\n\n### Potential issue\n- **`Framework` symbol** — It defines choices (`net8.0`/`net9.0`) but has no `replaces` property. Unless the source files use the exact symbol name `Framework` via other conventions, the chosen value won't actually be substituted into the project file's `<TargetFramework>`.\n\n### Looks good\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `sourceName`, `author`, `classifications`, and `tags` are all correctly defined.\n\n**TL;DR:** At minimum, add a `description` field and verify the `Framework` symbol is wired up to your `.csproj` before publishing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e82cb065-bfac-478f-8124-4274077cbc72","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json against the .NET template engine schema requirements for publishing to NuGet.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but highly recommended for validation and editor support. The standard value is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet publishing so templates can be grouped (e.g., when multiple languages share a template).\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Not strictly required but useful when multiple versions of a template exist.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Not required but commonly set.\n   \nThe `description` field i